I figured it out, but there are some pitfalls. *the `__init__` method of the `rom.Model` must be called*. If the `__init__`  method of the child class is to be overridden - this is certainly the case if the `__init__` method of the parent class (the main parent class and not `rom.Model`) is to be called, then `rom.Model.__init__` *must be called before any persisted properties are set in the main parent's `__init__`*.  Also, *the child class\` `__init__` can not have any mandatory arguments. e.g:

```
class Base():
  def __init__(self, p1):
    self.p1

class Child(Base, rom.Model):
  p1 = rom.TextField()
  p2 = rom.TextField() # additional properties can be defined
  def __init__(self, p1='a', **kwargs):
    rom.Model.__init__(self, p1=p1)
    Base.__init__(self, p1)
```

Please mention if there is anything else is to be noted.

