The console consumer should also be started with `--bootstrap-server localhost:9092` as opposed to `--zookeeper`. If you fail to use `--bootstrap-server` the console consumer will use the old consumer rather than the `new` consumer.

@pganssle My problem with the `tzwinlocal` repr is that per the python standard docs on [repr](https://docs.python.org/2/library/functions.html#func-repr):
> For many types, this function makes an attempt to return a string that would yield an object with the same value when passed to eval(), otherwise the representation is a string enclosed in angle brackets that contains the name of the type of the object together with additional information often including the name and address of the object.

Thus it should be `tzwinlocal` or possibly return an equivalent object repr such as `tzstr('Eastern Standard Time')` which may make more sense as it would create an equivalent time zone regardless of the local time zone at the time of recreation of the object.  Although this would only work if you could assert that the `tzwinlocal` name and `tzstr` objects would be equal.

Two possible solutions:

- Use a custom DateTime field that can take datetimes as input

```python
from marshmallow import Schema, fields
import datetime

class MyDateTime(fields.DateTime):
    
    def _deserialize(self, val):
        if isinstance(val, datetime.datetime):
            val = val.isoformat()
        return fields.DateTime._deserialize(self, val)

class ASchema(Schema):
    x = MyDateTime()

schema = ASchema()
begin = {'x': datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(239482596)}
assert 'x' not in schema.validate(begin)
```

- Convert values in a `pre_load` hook (2.0/dev branch only)

```python
from marshmallow import Schema, fields, pre_load

class ASchema(Schema):
    x = fields.DateTime()
    
    @pre_load
    def convert_datetimes(schema, in_data):
        in_data['x'] = in_data['x'].isoformat()
        return in_data
```

