@djangochamp : this is expected behaviour of Fedex API - it treats everything that happens outside the US as international transactions (even though in fact it happens within the same foreign country - India, in your case). 

Therefore the current version of the library will generate the error you reported. 

Please be patient and watch my pull request per https://github.com/python-fedex-devs/python-fedex/pull/84 - once it is approved/integrated, the library will start supporting international transactions over Fedex.

```
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <vector>
#include <list>

namespace py = pybind11;

struct Foo {
        Foo(): x(){}
        template< typename Range>
        Foo( const Range& r): x(std::begin(r), std::end(r)){}
        std::vector< int> x;
};

//## Define the module
//This is where we actually define the `ctl` module. We'll also have a `phat` module that's written
PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
  //Create the module object. First arg is the name, second is the module docstring.
  py::module m("example", "Minimal Example.");

